  "doi": "10.1093/protein/gzm033",
  "title": "Crystal structures of high affinity human T-cell receptors bound to peptide major histocompatibility complex reveal native diagonal binding geometry.",
  "journal": "Protein engineering, design & selection : PEDS",
  "year": 2007,
  "authors": "Sami M, Rizkallah PJ, Dunn S, Molloy P, Moysey R, Vuidepot A, Baston E, Todorov P, Li Y, Gao F, Boulter JM, Jakobsen BK."
 },
 "executive_summary": "The study presents crystal structures of three in vitro-engineered, high-affinity TCRs recognizing the tumor-associated peptide NY-ESO(157-165) (SLLMWITQC) presented on MHC-I, alongside comparison with the parental wild-type TCR. Despite achieving affinities substantially higher than natural TCRs (which typically range 1\u2013100 \u03bcM), the engineered TCRs maintain the same diagonal binding geometry and overall docking mode as the wild-type, with affinity gains arising from CDR2 and CDR3 mutations that work synergistically to increase interface area, improve shape complementarity (particularly for the central methionine and tryptophan peptide residues), and add hydrogen-bonding interactions. The structures reveal an induced-fit mechanism in which CDR3 loop restructuring enables better peptide recognition and binding. These findings are relevant to TCR engineering for cancer immunotherapy, demonstrating that affinity enhancement for tumor neoantigens can be achieved within the constraints of the conserved TCR-MHC binding geometry, informing rational design strategies for therapeutic TCR variants.",
 "noncanonical": {
